<Post
  title="About"
  description="Sai Sri Ram Sribhashyam — AI systems, labor markets, and digital public infrastructure across 15 countries."
  backHref="/"
  backLabel="Home"
>
  <p class="lead">
    I build AI systems that help institutions see what's actually happening in
    labor markets — and help people navigate them.
  </p>

  <h2>The arc</h2>

  <p>
    I studied at BITS Pilani, then spent four years at Mu Sigma building
    predictive analytics for pharmaceutical clients. The work was technically
    interesting but felt disconnected from anything that mattered. I wanted to
    understand why some people got to participate in economies and others didn't.
  </p>

  <p>
    That led to Grameen Foundation, then to a decade straddling the World Bank
    and development consulting — building digital credentialing platforms in
    Sub-Saharan Africa, running NLP pipelines over a hundred thousand job
    postings in MENA, advising the government of Andhra Pradesh on AI for
    education-to-employment at the level of five ministries.
  </p>

  <p>
    Most recently at the Tony Blair Institute. Currently in San Francisco,
    thinking about what it means to build AI for development in the 2030s.
  </p>

  <h2>Two moments that shaped the work</h2>

  <p>
    On Mt. Kigali, over dinner with a University of Rwanda student who had a
    Master's in IoT and couldn't find work. Not because she lacked skill.
    Because no employer could see what she knew. That conversation became the
    compass for the credentialing work that followed — and for most of what
    came after.
  </p>

  <p>
    In a room in Andhra Pradesh with ministers who had agreed, after months of
    work, to share data across five ministries to build an AI-enabled
    education-to-employment platform. The technical challenge was tractable.
    The political economy challenge — getting five departments to trust a shared
    system — was the real work. That's usually true.
  </p>

  <h2>What I'm interested in now</h2>

  <p>
    Senior roles at the intersection of AI and international development.
    Organizations trying to build things that last — that are still running
    five years after the project ends. Based in San Francisco, open to remote
    and travel-heavy work.
  </p>

  <p>
    If you're building something in this space, I'd like to hear about it.
  </p>

